==================== CORE JAVA ====================

1. Difference between HashMap and ConcurrentHashMap
a) HashMap is non-thread-safe; ConcurrentHashMap is thread-safe with fine-grained locking.
b) HashMap allows null keys/values and is faster in single-threaded contexts. ConcurrentHashMap uses bucket-level locking (or CAS in newer JDKs) to allow concurrent reads/writes without blocking the entire map.

2. Difference between HashMap, ConcurrentHashMap, Hashtable
a) Hashtable is legacy synchronized, HashMap is non-synchronized, ConcurrentHashMap is modern thread-safe.
b) Hashtable locks the entire map (poor scalability). HashMap is faster but unsafe in concurrency. ConcurrentHashMap improves scalability with segment/bucket-level locks and disallows null keys/values.

3. How HashMap works internally?
a) HashMap stores entries in buckets using hashCode and equals.
b) It uses an array of buckets, applies hashCode() to determine index, resolves collisions via linked lists or balanced trees (since JDK 8). Rehashing occurs when load factor exceeds threshold.

4. JVM Memory Model (Heap, Stack, Metaspace)
a) Heap stores objects, Stack stores method frames, Metaspace stores class metadata.
b) Heap is divided into Young/Old generations, Stack holds local variables and call frames, Metaspace (post-Java 8) stores class definitions replacing PermGen.

5. Java Memory Areas
a) Heap, Stack, Metaspace, Code Cache.
b) Heap for objects, Stack for execution, Metaspace for class metadata, Code Cache for JIT compiled code.

6. Comparable vs Comparator
a) Comparable defines natural ordering; Comparator defines custom ordering.
b) Comparable implemented in class (compareTo), Comparator is external (compare). Comparator allows multiple sorting strategies.

7. Multithreading & synchronization issues
a) Race conditions occur without synchronization.
b) Threads accessing shared resources can cause inconsistent states. Synchronization (locks, volatile, atomic classes) ensures visibility and ordering.

8. Functional Interfaces & Lambda expressions
a) Functional interfaces have one abstract method; lambdas implement them concisely.
b) Examples: Runnable, Callable, Predicate. Lambdas reduce boilerplate and enable functional programming.

9. ExecutorService, Callable, Future
a) ExecutorService manages threads, Callable returns results, Future holds async result.
b) ExecutorService abstracts thread pools, Callable allows checked exceptions and return values, Future provides result retrieval and cancellation.

10. Checked vs Unchecked Exceptions
a) Checked must be declared/handled; Unchecked are runtime.
b) Checked (IOException) enforce handling at compile time. Unchecked (NullPointerException) occur at runtime without declaration.

11. Optional: orElse vs orElseGet
a) orElse always evaluates; orElseGet evaluates lazily.
b) orElse executes even if value present, orElseGet executes supplier only if empty.

12. Synchronized vs ReentrantLock
a) Synchronized is implicit; ReentrantLock is explicit with more features.
b) ReentrantLock supports tryLock, fairness, interruptible locks. Synchronized is simpler but less flexible.

13. Optimistic vs Pessimistic Locking
a) Optimistic assumes no conflict; Pessimistic prevents conflict by locking.
b) Optimistic uses versioning (CAS), retries on conflict. Pessimistic locks resource upfront, reducing concurrency.

14. String intern() method
a) Intern stores string in pool to reuse.
b) intern() returns reference from string pool, saving memory and enabling == comparison.

15. == vs equals()
a) == compares references; equals() compares values.
b) For objects, == checks memory address, equals() can be overridden for logical equality.

16. Thread safety & concurrency
a) Thread safety ensures consistent state under concurrency.
b) Achieved via immutability, synchronization, atomic classes, concurrent collections.

17. OutOfMemoryError causes & troubleshooting
a) Caused by memory leaks or insufficient heap.
b) Common causes: large objects, unclosed resources, excessive caching. Troubleshoot via heap dumps, GC logs, profiling.

18. How to make class thread-safe?
a) Use immutability, synchronization, or concurrent utilities.
b) Immutable classes are inherently safe. Synchronize shared state or use ConcurrentHashMap, AtomicInteger.
